<h1>To Adam Stephen</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Winchester Decr 28th 1755</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Captn John Mercer only returnd last night from Williamsburg and brings no satisfactory answers to any thing I questiond the Governor upon.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> The express that was sent to Genl Shirley is returnd, without seeing him: however the Governor writes that he expects answers to his Letters by Colo. Hunter, who is now at New York and waits the arrival of the Genl at that place. The Governor is very strongly of opinion that Captn Dagworthy has no right to contend<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> the Command; and in his Letter to me<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> saysafter mentioning the return of the express and his expectancy of satisfactory Lettersbut I am of opinion you might have obviated the inconsistent dispute with Captn Dagworthy, by asking him if he did not command a Provinl Compay by virtue of Govr Sharpes Comn as that he had formerly from his Majesty now ceases as he is not on the half Pay list. If so, the method you are to take is very obvious, as your Comission from me is greater than what he has and in Williamsburg when I was down there, both he and Colo. Fitzhugh<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> told me, that Dagworthy could have no more pretensions to Command me or either of the Field Officers of the Virga Regt than we have to comd Genl Shirleyand further gave it as their opinions; that as Dagworthys was only a botchd up Comn at best and as he commanded a provencial Company and by virtue of a Governors Comn that he ought to be arrested for his presumptionthey sayallowg his Comn from the King to be valid; yet as he is not there by order of his Majesty, that he can have no better pretensions than a visiting half pay Officer who transiently passes thr the Camp to assume the ComdI wish you woud sound him on this hd; and hear how he will answer these things and let me know when you come down which I desire may be immediately as<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> I want much to consult you
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-02-02-pb-0239">[239]</span>
upon several accounts. The Paymaster, and Commissary if he is not very much engagd must accompany you[.] Desire both to have their accts settled and brought with them as that is necessary before I can give more money. Also desire all the Officers who have receivd money for Recruitg to make up their accts immediately and charge for no more Men than has<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0006" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> actually been receivd at the severall Rendezvousesallowance will be made for no othersthe Arrears of Pay, for those Officers and Soldiers who have not recd for the Months of Jany and Feby are im[mediatel]y to be made out and sent down by you with the Rec[ruitin]g accts;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0007" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> desire them to charge for no Men but what are present, as I can pay for no others now.</p>
<p>I have sent you one of the Mutiny Bills which I recd from belowbut I thinkindeed I believe it is absolutely necessary as we still want the powerto postpone tryal till after your return<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0008" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0008-ptr">8</a>Order Comy Walker to see that there is particular care taken of all the Bags and to send them down if more Salt is wantedAlso order him to call upon Mr McLean to render an acct of the disbursements of Sundry sums to the amount of 70s let him have since the 17th of Septr last and bring that down with him.</p>
<p>Inclosd is a Commission for Captn Waggener which I have neglected giving before, so long as I have had itdesire him, as the comd will upon your leaving the place, devolve upon him to be very circumspect in his dutyand to see that the Troops are duly drawn out and traind to their exercise and practisd to bush fighting. As I expect in a very few days to have the pleasure of seeing you I shall only add that I am Yr most Obt Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC</span>: Adam Stephen Papers; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
 Four minor changes in the letter book have been noted.</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>John Mercer took <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0203" class="document">GWs letter of 5 Dec. to Dinwiddie</a> and left Williamsburg on 16 Dec., probably with <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0214" class="document">Dinwiddies letter to GW of 14 Dec.</a> from which he quotes here.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The word for is inserted in the letter book after contend.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The letter book substitutes he for to me.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>William Fitzhugh, burgess from Stafford County, was a member of the committee appointed to supervise expenditure of the 40,000 appropriated for defense of the colony. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0014&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-02-02-0014-fn-0002#GEWN-02-02-02-0014-fn-0002" class="document">GW to Charles Dick, 6 Sept. 1755, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>The letter book has and instead of as.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>The letter book substitutes have for has.</p>

</div>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-02-02-pb-0240">[240]</span>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>For the Arrears of Pay due for Jan. and Feb. 1755, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0191&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-02-02-0191-fn-0008#GEWN-02-02-02-0191-fn-0008" class="document">Peter Hog to GW, 29 Nov. 1755, n.8</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0250" class="document">GWs After Orders, 30 Dec. 1755</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-02-02-02-0242-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-02-02-0203&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-02-02-0203-fn-0005#GEWN-02-02-02-0203-fn-0005" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, 5 Dec. 1755, n.5</a>, for references to the mutiny bill passed by the Virginia Assembly in early November.</p>

</div>
